39
00:02:30,730 --> 00:02:41,382
We all know firsthand that there's certain sections of the city that have been impacted by the change and basically what the FAA has tried to do is simplify the air

40
00:02:42,103 --> 00:02:42,903
travel routes.

41
00:02:43,043 --> 00:02:51,706
So back a year or so ago, a year and a half, the planes were dispersed over multiple cities throughout the Commonwealth.

42
00:02:52,146 --> 00:02:57,928
So when they took off, they were dispersed, so we all dealt with an occasional sound here and there, but nobody was impacted

43
00:02:58,388 --> 00:03:00,910
directly all day long with a certain sound.

44
00:03:01,290 --> 00:03:09,695
They try to simplify the skies, make travel lanes, and therefore it has brought about the volume that is going over one particular route in the city.

45
00:03:10,435 --> 00:03:13,617
There's actually quite an area over the Malden Hospital.

46
00:03:13,637 --> 00:03:20,121
It's where the planes that come off of runway 33L, they actually split, and they go in different directions.

47
00:03:20,201 --> 00:03:23,122
So that particular area gets hit very hard.

48
00:03:23,723 --> 00:03:27,225
And in a lot of the studies that the community groups have done,

49
00:03:27,605 --> 00:03:32,688
They're actually looking at the Stearns Ave area as being hit very, very hard in our community.

50
00:03:33,428 --> 00:03:37,270
So what we talked to the FAA about was, what are you going to do about it?

51
00:03:37,390 --> 00:03:38,751
We're all dealing with this issue.

52
00:03:38,791 --> 00:03:43,314
It's a quality of life issue in our neighborhood and the surrounding communities, and what are you going to do?

53
00:03:44,214 --> 00:03:51,838
And they basically told us that they have MIT, Massport has commissioned MIT to do a formal study, but it will not be ready until next fall.

54
00:03:51,898 --> 00:03:55,100
So a year from now, they'll get the results of the sound

55
00:03:55,612 --> 00:03:58,614
testing that they have commissioned through Massport.

56
00:03:59,195 --> 00:04:02,177
And of course, we all said that's not good enough.

57
00:04:03,018 --> 00:04:04,159
Go back to the way it was.

58
00:04:04,239 --> 00:04:05,200
Do something different.

59
00:04:05,780 --> 00:04:08,983
And the FAA's position is that it's all about safety.

60
00:04:09,303 --> 00:04:12,666
Their main concern above and beyond sound is safety for

61
00:04:13,246 --> 00:04:18,789
the flights, the people on the planes, the pilots, and the workers, and the FAA in general.

62
00:04:19,590 --> 00:04:31,256
So they heard our cry for help, and not only is it that there are the numbers that are traveling down these roads in the sky, but the elevation, the volume,

63
00:04:32,624 --> 00:04:36,565
which are two of the main concerns that are also causing havoc in our area.

64
00:04:37,245 --> 00:04:38,625
So they listened intently.

65
00:04:39,226 --> 00:04:44,187
They said that they were going to reach out through Massport and try to get some more information quicker.

66
00:04:44,667 --> 00:04:54,589
We actually do have a sound study that's part of Massport that's set up in Magoon Thatcher area and that they do not have the results from that yet.

67
00:04:55,109 --> 00:04:57,911
So once they get those results, they will be forthcoming to us.

68
00:04:58,472 --> 00:05:05,417
They use a 65 decibel as their magic number, and that's what they've been using as their level that is tolerable.

69
00:05:06,258 --> 00:05:16,485
And so I know what I mentioned to them is that they need to stop looking at things from the sky, and they need to come down to the neighborhoods and see the real impact that it's causing on our citizens.

70
00:05:17,306 --> 00:05:35,332
